Subject:    Re:  Nicknames and Abbreviations
From:       <a href="?a=95837692300025&r=1&w=2">Ruth Brungardt &lt;moose%sri-pluto () sri-tsc&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198505">1985-05-02 10:58:54</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426413&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426413&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Concern has been expressed over the ability to use 
nicknames and abbreviations for domain-style names.
Completion Queries and Responses is a solution for 
some of the concerns.  This is an optional feature 
for servers, but one that may be found worth the
implementation effort.

Given a partial domain name, qtype, qclass, and target
domain, a server will search for names beginning with
the partial string.  It will return either the best 
match or all possible completions as specified by the 
query type (CQUERYM or CQUERYU).  RFC 882 (p. 26) and 
RFC 883 (p.19) give more information on these interactions.

A smart telnet program will use this mechanism to resolve
"telnet mc" to "telnet mc.mit.edu".  For situations in which
a true nickname rather than an abbreviation is used, standard
CNAME queries or some other mechanism will be more appropriate.

Ruth Brungardt

